Cases of hand, foot and mouth disease virus Infection in Daycares
-----------------------------------------------------------------
A total of 5 to 10 cases of hand, foot and mouth disease virus
infection have been reported at area daycares, Waco physician Dr. Tim
Martindale confirmed on Thu 27 Oct 2011. This common virus usually
affects infants and children younger than 5, although it can sometimes
occur in adults. Symptoms include sores in the mouth and a skin rash
along with congestion, fever and body aches.

It typically runs its course in 3 to 5 days, Martindale said. The best
defense against the virus is frequent hand washing and avoidance of
close contact such as kissing, hugging or sharing eating utensils with
those who have the disease.

It shouldn't be confused with foot and mouth disease, which affects
cattle, pigs and sheep, but not humans.

--
