[Large outbreaks of hand, foot, and mouth disease are not common in
the United States, and the disease is rarely reported. However, in
some countries in Asia, outbreaks are large and occur often. Thousands
of people may get infected during these outbreaks. Some people,
particularly young children, may have severe disease requiring
hospitalization or even causing death.

Hand, foot, and mouth disease is caused by several different viruses
classified in the genus _Enterovirus_, which comprises the
polioviruses, coxsackieviruses, echoviruses, and enteroviruses.
Coxsackievirus A16 has been the most common cause of hand, foot and
mouth disease in the United States, but other coxsackieviruses have
been associated with the illness. Currently in several Asian countries
enterovirus 71 is associated with more severe forms of hand, foot and
mouth disease.

The current outbreak in Texas appears to be dispersed and affecting
relatively few children. A detailed account of hand, foot and mouth
disease can be obtained from the CDC website at:
http://www.cdc.gov/hand-foot-mouth/about/index.html. - Mod.CP

The interactive HealthMap/ProMED map for Texas is available at:
http://healthmap.org/r/1mfK - CopyEd.EJP]
